snippet.textDisplay: G,, D,,,  !!   Buck Rodgers !   Most of you are not old enough to have watched 1950' s  or 1960's black and white TV.      To be clear,, Buck Rodger's landing space ship looked exactly like that.   To have spanned seasons many, when Airlines were flying propeller driven craft, with not a scrap of electronics on board save a radio, weather forecasting was just as accurate in Poor Richard's Almanac as the evening news, gasoline was 0.18 per gallon,, and your oil was checked and windshield washed while you waited, a dishwasher was only the person who drew the short straw, and garbage was burned in the pile behind the shred. Telephones had 4 numbers and if you needed long distance,, you clicked the receiver two or three times to alert Mabel, so she could plug your line into the line for long distance.  I rode in DC-3's when they were as young as a  decade old,, and on one of the first 707's headed for Disneyland on a summer vacation.   And feel what I feel when it is clear,, that had I enough money,, I might well be able to buy a ticket to go see Mars.  Mars.   Buck Rodgers has arrived.

snippet.textDisplay:
One of the many things I love about SpaceX is the genuine energy of their crew. Utilizing their actual science and engineering staff for their public representatives is an absolutely genius decision. Their honest enthusiasm, warmth and competence is inspirational. The beginnings of StarFleet and the United Federation of Planets. It may only start with humans as a multi-planetary species, but who knows what the future holds hundreds of years from now.


We need to aspire to be better. Thank you for leading the way. Thanks to all who came before, and thanks to NASA for their continued support both technically and in financial terms. SpaceX would never have gotten to this point without the foundation created by NASA and the generations of scientists and engineers who came before.


What a great time to be alive!
